President Obama released a statement mourning the death of Elie Wiesel, a Holocaust survivor and human rights activist. The President described Wiesel as a moral voice and the conscience of the world. He expressed his gratitude for the friendship they shared and their discussions on topics such as friendship and their commitment to the State of Israel. Obama highlighted Wiesel's role as a living memorial and his dedication to combating anti-Semitism, hatred, bigotry, and intolerance. He emphasized the importance of upholding the duty of memory and the need for individuals and nations to stand against injustice. The President acknowledged Wiesel's impact as a writer, speaker, activist, and thinker, and urged people to be better and summon their capacity for good. Obama concluded by expressing gratitude that Wiesel never gave up on humanity and emphasized the importance of treating one another with dignity and respect.